rs of “illicit” magic and inquiries into natural philosophy, delegitimizing certain practices and thus shaping the development of early modern science. Describing the dynamics of censorship that continued well into the post-Reformation era, Defining Nature's Limits is revisionist history that will interest scholars of the history science, the history of magic, and the history of the church alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aInquisitionzItalyxHistory. 0aMagiczItalyxHistory. 0aReligion and sciencezItalyxHistory. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  acensorship, science, Protestant Reformation, natural world, learned magic, inquisition, scholastic traditions, social discipline.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226819433423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226819433/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles